@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(iv) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it builds a RECORD (`#{ x: 3, y: 4 }`) and reads a field — a heap
-- value the compute spine has no representation for yet. The differential harness must
-- report it `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at the compiler frontier — never a
-- miscompile, never a JS crash.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors (Ok/Error/Some/None + user `type` variants — see compile_ctor_test).
-- The frontier now sits at the remaining heap values — records, lists, closures. This
-- file builds a RECORD, so it still refuses; when records lower (a later D1 slice), it
-- flips from `unsupported` to a print with no edit.

type Point = { x: Number, y: Number }

def originX(p: Point): Number
  p.x

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  println(originX(#{ x: 3, y: 4 }))
